Model 2: add the covariate wind speed to the model and use the likelihood ratio test to test of this covariate is needed

Add the covariate wind speed to the model

m2 <- update(m1, .~. + Wind)

## F-statistic: 44.09 on 2 and 108 DF,  p-value: 1.003e-14

Use the likelihood ratio test to test of this covariate is needed

# Calculate chi-squared statistics, which is -2 loglikelihood difference 
chi_stat <- -2 *(logLik(m1) - logLik(m2))[1]
# Calculate p value
pchisq(chi_stat, df = 1, lower.tail = F)
## [1] 5.843457e-13
# Or simply use lrtest function from lmtest package
lmtest::lrtest(m1, m2)
## Likelihood ratio test
## 
## Model 1: Ozone ~ Solar.R
## Model 2: Ozone ~ Solar.R + Wind
##   #Df  LogLik Df  Chisq Pr(>Chisq)    
## 1   3 -538.86                         
## 2   4 -512.91  1 51.899  5.843e-13 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

But it makes more sense if we compare the partial F test in this case

anova(m1, m2)

Q1.4

Plot the observed ozone level versus the predicated values of model 1 and model 2 and calculate the correlation between the observed and the predicted data for the two models

mytheme1 <- function(...) {
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(size = 0.3),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10, color = "black", hjust=1),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10, color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, color = "black", hjust = 0.5),
    legend.position = "top"
    )
}

df_ozone_pred <- tibble(Ozone = airquality_complete$Ozone, 
                            Ozone_pred_m1 = fitted(m1), 
                            Ozone_pred_m2 = fitted(m2))


m1_corr <- cor.test(df_ozone_pred[[1]], df_ozone_pred[[2]])
m2_corr <- cor.test(df_ozone_pred[[1]], df_ozone_pred[[3]])

df_ozone_pred %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Ozone, y = Ozone_pred_m1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, shape = 21, fill = "#ae017e") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, size = 1.2) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 10), limits = c(0, 100)) + 
  annotate("text", x = 140, y = 0, 
           label = paste0("\u03c1 = ", round(m1_corr$estimate[[1]], 2),
           "; p-value = ", round(m1_corr$p.value[[1]], 3)), size = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
  mytheme1() +
  labs(
    title = "Model 1",
    x = "Actual values of Ozone",
    y = "Predictive values of Ozone"
  ) ->> F1

df_ozone_pred %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Ozone, y = Ozone_pred_m2)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, shape = 21, fill = "#02818a") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, size = 1.2, color = "#e31a1c") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 10), limits = c(0, 100)) +
  annotate("text", x = 140, y = 0, 
           label = paste0("\u03c1 = ", round(m2_corr$estimate[[1]], 2),
           "; p-value = ", round(m2_corr$p.value[[1]], 3)), size = 4) +
  theme_bw() +
  mytheme1() +
  labs(
    title = "Model 2",
    x = "Actual values of Ozone",
    y = "Predictive values of Ozone"
  ) ->> F2

gridExtra::grid.arrange(F1, F2, ncol = 2)

summary(anova3_2)
##                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)

Compute residual standard error

sqrt(sum(anova3_2$residuals^2)/anova3_2$df.residual)
